{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"17eb4c17-8aa1-4b96-8450-6944f2fb5eae","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` alone isn't enough. There are typically **three things** conspiring to keep your image inset:\n\n### 1. Hide Shell / NavigationPage chrome\nIf you're inside a `Shell` or `NavigationPage`, those add their own bars:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage ...\n    Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n    Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n```\n\n### 2. iOS — opt out of safe area insets\n```xml\n<ContentPage ...\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n### 3. Android — transparent system bars\nIn your `MainActivity.cs`, override `OnCreate` to draw behind system bars:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    if (Window is not null)\n    {\n        Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n(Add `using AndroidX.Core.View;` for `WindowCompat`.)\n\n> **Note:** .NET 10 targeting Android 15+ (SDK 35) enforces edge-to-edge by default, but you still need `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` and transparent bar colors for the content to actually render behind them.\n\n### Minimal full-screen page\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThat combination should give you true edge-to-edge rendering on both platforms.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4b496f47-ce79-483c-a887-4069e35d40f2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app on .NET 10, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. In .NET MAUI (especially .NET 8+), to achieve true edge-to-edge content, you need to do more than just set `SafeAreaEdges`. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. **`SafeAreaEdges`** - This is an iOS concept primarily. Setting it to `None` tells the page not to respect safe area insets on iOS.\n\n\n2. On Android, the approach is different—you need platform-specific configuration to make the window draw edge-to-edge, particularly with .NET 9/.NET 10's changes to how system bars are handled. For iOS, you'd use the platform-specific `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` property, while Android requires window-level settings to achieve the same effect.\n\nI'm realizing the user mentioned `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"`, which isn't a standard .NET MAUI property on `ContentPage`—they might be referencing something from a community toolkit or a custom implementation. The typical .NET MAUI approach involves platform-specific code rather than a single unified property. I'm realizing the user's real problem is likely one of several common culprits: they might need to disable the safe area on iOS, explicitly enable edge-to-edge rendering on Android with transparent system bars, or they could be inadvertently adding padding through Shell navigation chrome or a NavigationPage wrapper. Let me give them a focused answer covering these main causes and their fixes.","outputTokens":1597},"id":"367323fe-9e59-4651-b72d-2457d3502167","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:53:15.184Z","parentId":"cf294068-1b3d-4212-8936-01842265646c"}
